{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636331"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:27:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:27:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17580"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17580","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17580"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10270"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71375"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10270","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10270"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17580"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56852"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10074"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23991"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24008"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71375","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71375"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ELipoproteins are essential for transporting hydrophobic lipids through the aqueous blood. The liver produces several classes of these particles.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of very low density lipoprotein?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Delivers hepatic triglycerides to peripheral tissues","Carries dietary cholesterol to the liver","Returns excess tissue cholesterol to the liver","Transports intestinal fatty acids to fat cells","Exchanges membrane phospholipids between cells"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of very low density lipoprotein (VLDL) is to \u003Cstrong\u003Edeliver hepatic triglycerides to peripheral tissues\u003C/strong\u003E. These particles are assembled in liver cells and transport endogenous triglycerides to muscle and fat tissue, where lipoprotein lipase releases the fatty acids for energy production or storage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarries dietary cholesterol to the liver\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes chylomicron function\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReturns excess tissue cholesterol to the liver\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the role of high density lipoprotein in reverse cholesterol transport\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransports intestinal fatty acids to fat cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Chylomicrons, not VLDL, carry dietary fats\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExchanges membrane phospholipids between cells\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not a major function of any lipoprotein class\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs tissues remove triglycerides from VLDL particles, they become denser intermediate density lipoproteins (IDL) and eventually low density lipoproteins (LDL). The structural integrity of these particles is maintained by apolipoprotein B-100.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Very low density lipoproteins (VLDL) are assembled in hepatocytes to distribute endogenous triglycerides throughout the body","VLDL particles contain apolipoprotein B-100 which provides structural stability","As peripheral tissues remove triglycerides from VLDL, the particles become progressively denser, forming IDL then LDL"],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56852"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17580"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56852"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-18T09:29:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-18T09:30:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10270"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71375"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tag